  "why": "PVDF-HFP-SN-0.1LAWTP is used as a solid composite electrolyte for Li-ion batteries. It shows optimum ionic conductivities of 3.03×10^-5 S/cm at 30°C and 1×10^-4 S/cm at 50°C (Fig. 4a–b). The electrochemical stability window (decomposition voltage) is 4.8 V (Fig. 4e). The Li+ transference number is 0.478 at 50°C (Table 2; Fig. 6c–d). In Li/Li symmetric cells, it maintains stable plating/stripping for 1000 cycles at 0.1 mA/cm^2 without short circuit and with lower, stable polarization (Fig. 7b). In LFP/PVDF-HFP-SN-0.1LAWTP/Li cells at 50°C and 0.5C, the initial specific capacity is 158.06 mAh/g and 133.82 mAh/g after 200 cycles (84.66% retention) (Fig. 8b,d). At room temperature, it delivers 142.69 mAh/g initially and 136.41 mAh/g after 500 cycles (95.60% retention; CE >99% after the initial cycle) (Fig. 9b,d). With 5 μL liquid electrolyte infiltration (same membrane under modified condition), ionic conductivity increases to 3.64×10^-4 S/cm at 30°C and 7×10^-4 S/cm at 50°C and t_Li+ is 0.323, while the stability window is ~4.5 V (Fig. 5; Fig. S5)."
}

